\begin_layout Section
Overview
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Organize my files and file systems in a complete, standardized manner which
 is easy to access and parse.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Context
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Most of my work and many of my personal thoughts and memories are kept digitally
, usually on a Linux ext4 file-system in my personal computer.
 As the size and number of files increases, it becomes difficult to keep
 all of that information ordered, which then causes issues and delays when
 trying to locate important information, especially if it's fairly old.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While as mentioned my central work environment is on my personal computer
 in a Linux environment, I actually have four environments where I keep
 files and use regularly.
 Each is named, under my general username theme of All-Seeing:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
AllSeer
\series default
: the Linux environment on my personal computer, via dual boot
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
NoSeer
\series default
: the Windows environment on my personal computer, via dual boot
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
MiniSeer
\series default
: the Android environment on my personal smartphone
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
GSeer
\series default
: the file system on my personal Google Drive account.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
AllSeer, MiniSeer and NoSeer are all separate from each other and keep their
 files locally.
 GSeer is stored on the cloud (on Google servers) and can be accessed via
 the Google Drive web app.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When possible, I prefer to mount the file systems on one another for easy
 access.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As I prefer a Linux environment, I try to use Linux emulators that can access
 the file system, if such emulators exist.
 On NoSeer, the app CygWin is installed, which can run many Linux programs
 and has access to the windows file system.
 On MiniSeer, I have TEL installed, a modified version of Termux, a Linux
 distribution/emulator that can also access the Android file system.
 Termux does not follow standard Linux file structure and some script paths
 may change for it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Goals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\bar under
210630A
\bar default
 Be able to quickly locate a file on any file system I'm using based only
 on its name or contents.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\bar under
210630B
\bar default
 Create a ubiquitous structure standard for each of my file systems (phone,
 Linux, Windows, etc), that takes into consideration File-System Mounting,
 System Directories, App Configurations, System Configurations, Project
 Directories, Archive Directories and Automation Scripts
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\bar under
210630C
\bar default
 Create 
\emph on
Project Directory
\emph default
 and 
\emph on
Archive Directory
\emph default
 specifications for 
\shape slanted
CONTROL/System210606B
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\bar under
210606D
\bar default
 Specify backup procedures for my files
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\bar under
210606E
\bar default
 Specify cloud and synchronization solutions for each of my projects, and
 specifically allow synchronization of project and archive directories between
 file systems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Systems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection

\bar under
210630A
\bar default
 Home Directories
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each file system will have a defined 
\emph on
Home Directory
\emph default
.
 Excluding system and app files as necessary, I will only edit and write
 files inside that directory (reading is allowed everywhere).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The home directory may contain app configuration or data folders only as
 necessary, and if possible they must be hidden.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Specifically:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
AllSeer's
\series default
 home directory is
\family typewriter
 /home/atai
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
NoSeer's 
\series default
home directory is 
\family typewriter
C:
\backslash
Users
\backslash
ataya
\backslash
Home
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
MiniSeer's
\series default
 home directory is 
\family typewriter
/data/data/com.termux/files/home
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
GSeer's
\series default
 home directory is 
\family typewriter
My Drive
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ideally, the home directory is local (for better speeds) and supports symbolic
 and hard links.
 If possible, then when its directories are explored normally, and both
 in terminal and in file explorer, only personal or manually created files
 are displayed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If environment variables are supported, the HOME variable should lead here.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The file explorer should have the home directory bookmarked (be it automatically
 via HOME variable or manually).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If possible, the home directory should be the default directory when opening
 a file explorer or a terminal emulator.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The home directories should be as synchronized as possible between devices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When describing paths, I may write 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

~
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 instead of the project directory paths.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection

\bar under
210630B
\bar default
 Project & Aspect directories
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In each home directory (as enumerated in 
\shape slanted
System210630A
\shape default
), there should be a directory for each aspect detailed in 
\shape slanted
CONTROL/System210606A
\shape default
, named identically to them: Red, Purple, Green, Gray, Steel and Blue.
 These will be called 
\emph on
Aspect Directory
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each project's 
\emph on
Project Directory
\emph default
 (as ruled by 
\shape slanted
CONTROL/System210606B
\shape default
) will be a sub-directory of its aspect's directory, named identically to
 the project.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Though project may delineate systems that request rulings or expansions
 in other projects—for example as CONTROL demands FILER to detail the structure
 and location of Project Directories—any of the files its own systems demands
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
excepting project statements as detailed in 
\shape slanted
CONTROL/System210606C 
\shape default
and all systems in this project
\end_layout

\end_inset

 must remain within its project directory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If two systems from different projects require work on the same file, the
 file should be created in the project directory of one of them and then
 linked (symbolically or not, as deemed appropriate,) in the other one.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Other than maintaining a project statement in the top level of the directory
 (as detailed in 
\shape slanted
CONTROL/System210606C
\shape default
) and a symbolic link to its archive directory (as detailed in 
\shape slanted
System210630C
\shape default
), a project directory should be freely structured within the systems of
 its project.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The visible contents of the home directories should be mostly identical
 and synced between my four devices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection

\bar under
210704A
\series medium
\bar default
 
\series default
Projects Shortcut Directory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the top level of the home directory, an additional directory called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Projects
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 should be created and contain symbolic links to each project directory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The symbolic links should be relative (e.g 
\family typewriter
../Gray/FILER
\family default
 rather than 
\family typewriter
/home/atai/Gray/FILER
\family default
).
 This is to make backup and restore easier across devices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The purpose of this is to make access to known projects more easily, while
 having a more categorical overview if needed (in the form of the aspect
 directories,) and avoiding long messy lists.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection

\bar under
210630C
\bar default
 Archive Directories & Archiving
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the top level of this Project Directory, there should be an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Archives
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 directory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Archives directory should have a sub-directory for each project named
 of the form 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

{ID}.{PROJECT}{SIGN}
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, where ID is the project ID, PROJECT is the project's name and sign is
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

+
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 if the project is ongoing, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

-
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 if it's frozen and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 otherwise.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A project's system should specify archiving procedures that will run as
 long as the project is ongoing.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The archiving systems should remove project files that are no longer relevant
 to it, but preserve files that could be used as reference or simply for
 memory; these files should be placed in the archive directory and structured
 according to the archiving system or systems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As long as at least one of a project's systems is actively practiced, it
 is considered 
\emph on
ongoing.
 
\emph default
All of the above systems apply to it, and its archive directory should be
 suffixed with 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

+
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When an ongoing project has no active systems and they are not meant to
 be activated again for at least 3 months, the project should be considered
 
\emph on
archived
\emph default
 — any of its current contents that are deemed relevant for preservation
 should be moved to the archive directory, its project directory should
 be removed as long with its 
\family typewriter
~/Projects
\family default
 shortcut, and the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

+
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 suffix should be removed from its archived directory name.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When a project's systems are not meant to be practiced for two weeks at
 least but are meant to be activated again in at most 3 months, the project
 should be considered 
\emph on
frozen
\emph default
.
 Any files that are should be irrelevant for the reactivation should be
 removed or achieved according to their significance.
 Then, the remaining contents of the directory should move to a sub directory
 in the archive, called a 
\emph on
state archive
\emph default
.
 Then, the now empty project directory should be removed along with its
 
\family typewriter
~/Project 
\family default
link.
 The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

+
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 suffix of its archive directory should be replaced with 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

-
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When a frozen project is no longer meant to be reactivated, the content
 of its state archived should be examined and archived as deemed necessary.
 Then the state archived should be removed along with the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

-
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 suffix of the archive directory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The top level of each Project Directory should contain a symbolic link to
 its archive, named 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Archive
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A major currently ongoing task of this system is the handling of previously
 created archives and structures that are currently revamped under the Foundatio
ns/Anchor theme (Summer 2021).
 
\end_layout

