\begin_layout Subsection

\bar under
210630E
\bar default
 Configuration Files
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A gray project should be opened to manage app and system configurations,
 and hold their directories.
 This includes shell startup and environment variables, system startup apps,
 preferences and settings for each app, URL to IP override, and so on.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With multitudes of apps that can be configured a variety of different ways.
 Outside order, customization and configuration are a mesa-objective in
 it of itself, and can have a lot of its own individual systems.
 Therefore, it should be managed in its own project.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Per rules by this project, should implement a system for backing up and
 syncing the configuration files, and contain the various configuration
 files.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection

\bar under
210706A
\bar default
 Cloud & Sync
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As per 
\shape slanted
Goal210606E
\shape default
 and as specified in 
\emph on
System210630B
\emph default
, I am seeking to sync my home directories between devices, and particularly
 Project Directories and Archive Directories.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each project should have a specified 
\emph on
Cloud Solution — 
\emph default
a way to backup its Project Directory into the cloud and sync it between
 devices.
 Such solution should generally keep the Project and Archive directories
 identical across file system through most points in time, but allow exclusions
 of system-specific files from the sync.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A Cloud Solution can be either 
\emph on
git
\emph default
, 
\emph on
Google
\emph default
, or
\emph on
 hard-drive, 
\emph default
each employed as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection

\bar under
210706A-1
\bar default
 git
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This actually refers to a combination of the Version Control System git,
 and the git repository hosting web app GitHub.
 The project directory should be initialized as a git repository.
 A bare repository should be initialized via GitHub, under the user AtaiAmbus.
 The bare repo should be set private.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After each session of work on the project, commit the changes into the git
 repository with an appropriate message, and push.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using git and GitHub as a cloud solution comes with a few convenient benefits:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
GitHub provides a simple and very straightforward way of browsing the files
 online, which will display text files as is and can also handle many common
 binary files (e.g JPEG, PDF).
 A project can be viewed easily and quickly from GitHub, and files can be
 very easily downloaded.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Works very well with projects centered around coding.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Syncing requires no additional apps and a project directory can be kept
 up to date with the simple command 
\family typewriter
git pull
\family default
, which can be ran periodically as a cron job or some similar service, usually
 to its full effect.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Version Control makes for additional backup and archiving measure, and can
 be viewed to get a better picture of the project.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main disadvantage of using 
\family typewriter
git
\family default
 is that it is very slow when large files are involved, and though GitHub
 allowed a very high ceiling of 100GB per repository, individual files cannot
 exceed the sometimes small 50MB.
 As a result, this cloud solution distinctly does not fit project with a
 lot of media files, and in general should be employed when the project
 mostly consists of text files.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If a file in a git project should be linked to another location, a symbolic
 link should be used, with the source at the git repository.
 Using a symbolic link the other way would cause git to only track the symlink
 path rather than the actual file, and git severs hard links when it pulls
 (though if deemed necessary, it seems they can be re-linked automatically
 with a 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "post merge hook"
target "https://stackoverflow.com/a/9322283/10913212"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that there is currently no way to access the actual files used with
 google apps (google docs, google slides, etc.), and sync/mount tools only
 offer links to the actual document or converted versions of it.
 As such, these files cannot be fully synced; instead they should be kept
 with web link desktop file (done automatically in the 
\family typewriter
google-drive-ocamlfuse
\family default
 mount, and a script should be written to generate them)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection

\bar under
210706A-2
\bar default
 Google
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More specifically, this solution uses the 
\emph on
Google Drive
\emph default
 app.
 The GSeer Project Directory becomes the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

main
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 project directory, and is synced with AllSeer, NoSeer and NoSeer automatically
 via available tools.
 If no tools are available to do this process automatically, Google API
 should be leveraged for a scripted push/pull that would be ran periodically.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Specifically, Google Drive sync tools available for each of the devices
 are as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
AllSeer:
\series default
 
\family typewriter

\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "drive"
target "https://github.com/odeke-em/drive"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\family default
 utility allows git-like push and pull.
 Alternatively, 
\family typewriter

\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "rclone sync"
target "https://rclone.org/commands/rclone_sync/"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\family default
 may be used for more traditional syncing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
NoSeer:
\series default
 A selective use of 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Google Drive Backup & Sync"
target "https://support.google.com/drive/answer/2374987#zippy="
literal "false"

\end_inset

 should suffice.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
MiniSeer: 
\series default

\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "FolderSync"
target "https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=dk.tacit.android.foldersync.lite&hl=en"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 seems to be a complete app for this.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is considered less convenient than git, the solution being far more
 variant across devices and therefore far more complicated to set up.
 Furthermore, it also uses one of the devices as a central host, which can
 hurt the idea of equal syncing.
 Still, this should be used if either
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The project contain many small media files, to the point where it would
 slow down git or be blocked from GitHub, but not to significantly hamper
 google's overall storage limit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The project uses primarily google app files.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first condition may apply to project that contain short videos and high
 quality pictures.
 If the overall size of the project exceeds roughly 500MB and does not exceed
 2GB, then it should fall in the appropriate range.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second condition mainly applies for non-code collaborative projects,
 due to google's friendly interface and the ease of simultaneous editing.
 The general reasoning for this condition is that in these cases, GSeer
 
\shape slanted
is
\shape default
 the central host, and that git cannot track changes in these files anyway;
 it would end up syncing mostly links.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection

\bar under
210706A-3
\series medium
\bar default
 
\series default
Hard Drive
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For this and 
\shape slanted
System210706B
\shape default
 a personal hard drive should be bought.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

host
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 repository of such project should be kept on my hard drive, and synced
 daily for new files.
 Each week, or when necessary, irrelevant files should be deleted from the
 project directories on each device, and relevant files copied from the
 hard drive.
 The project statement is always considered relevant for this purpose.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A file in a hard-drive synced project is considered 
\emph on
active 
\emph default
in a file system if it is present in its version of the project directory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A full index of the files on the hard drive should be kept as an appendix
 to the project statement, and each file in the index marked for the file
 system it is active at.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is generally intended for very heavy projects, that weigh many gigabytes
 of data — for example, seasons of TV shows, movies and so on.
 Using git or Google Drive on these project is infeasible, due to the size
 constraint outlined above.
 Regardless, such projects should generally not be fully synced, as they
 can weigh very on the file system.
 Rather, I opt for the solution above, which has a host repository on a
 separate, large drive, making all the data accessible and with relatively
 quick transfer, but allowing for more modular need-to-use system, to prevent
 the project from clogging up available storage and slowing down the computer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that it would be most easy to enact the synchronization via AllSeer,
 mounting the other file systems unto it.
 That way there is much less need to play with different connections and
 moving between devices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection

\bar under
210706B
\bar default
 Backup & Restore
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For this and 
\shape slanted
System210706A-3
\emph on
,
\shape default
\emph default
 a personal hard drive should be bought.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each week, the Home Directory should be backed up to the hard drive, using
 the Time Shift utility.
 This utility allows keeping versions of the directory throughout time,
 hard-linking shared files to preserve space.
 The various versions of the directory will be kept in a very straightforward
 way, available to navigate, in 
\family typewriter
/timeshift
\family default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each week, the system configuration and app configuration of each device
 should be backed up to the hard drive.
 The way to do this for each of the devices is as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
AllSeer
\series default
: Time Shift, excluding any visible (non dotfile) files in /home.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
NoSeer
\series default
: System Image Backup (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "here"
target "https://windowsloop.com/create-system-image-backup-windows-10/"
literal "false"

\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
MiniSeer: 
\series default
System Image with ADB.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Helium"
target "https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.koushikdutta.backupHelium"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 seems to provide a convenient interface for this.
 Otherwise look at this 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "StackOverflow answer"
target "https://stackoverflow.com/questions/19225467/backing-up-android-device-using-adb"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
GSeer requires no system backup, as it's purely storage of the home directory,
 and not an operating system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
GSeer also contains old data ranging from as early as 2010, all the way
 through to 2020.
 This should be backed up complelty, maybe even twice.
 And possibly removed from GSeer afterwards.
 An issue remains, in the fact that any local storage of drive files requires
 conversion to other formats in which data may be lost; transferring the
 archive into another owner could have anotther, similar effect.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Backups should be kept for the last 4 weeks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection

\bar under
210630F
\bar default
 Scripts and Automations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly to configuration files as per 
\shape slanted
System210630E
\shape default
, scripts and automations should be handled in a separate project.
 This is because automations and scripts are managed by additional concideration
s (under additional mesa objectives) than simply the organization of files.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The project should ensure apropriate distinctions between file systems,
 such that a file system does not have scripts that cannot run on it.
 Scripts should still be synced with the cloud.
 The project should make sure that apropriate scripts are found in the 
\family typewriter
PATH
\family default
 directories.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The project's aspect should be designated gray as it is a customization
 of the enviornment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection

\bar under
210710A
\bar default
 The /tmp Directory and Intended Creation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a general rule, each file which is created on the computer or transferred
 to it must have an intended use and therefore also a matching project.
 More specifically, actions are generally done to achieve some mesa-objective,
 which is generally be definition a project.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Simply put, any file which is relevant for a brief period of time (roughly
 three days or less) should be put in the 
\family typewriter
/tmp
\family default
 directory.
 Examples include: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Specific instructions before tests or IDF sorting
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Media reactions from instant-messaging apps
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Bug report screenshots
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Installation tarballs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Series episodes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
coding projects that are required for a specific run (e.g FRC projects).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Script testing files
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And so on.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When a new file has no appropriate project, creation of a new project should
 be considered; however, if no actual long term mesa-objective is relevant,
 it is presumed to be meant for a short concrete action, and therefore goes
 into 
\family typewriter
/tmp
\family default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Considering the premises above, 
\family typewriter
/tmp
\family default
 is determined as the default location of any newly created or newly transferred
 or downloaded files, especially ones that cannot be directly created or
 transferred into their appropriate location upon creation or transfer.
 Central applications of this include making 
\family typewriter
/tmp
\family default
 the default downloads directory and the screenshots directory, but it generally
 expands to any app or system function that creates or downloads files I'll
 later manually use — transmission's default download directory, LyX's default
 working directory, and so on.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is all nice and pretty, but the 
\family typewriter
/tmp 
\family default
directory really only exists on AllSeer.
 Its behaviour can be emulated though — CygWin's 
\family typewriter
C:
\backslash
cygwin64
\backslash
tmp 
\family default
and Termux's
\family typewriter
 /data/data/com.termux/usr/tmp
\family default
.
 Similar function can also be achived via a scheduled task to delete all
 files in the designated temporary directory.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For consistent access/location amoing filesystems, the tmp directory should
 be symbolically linked to 
\family typewriter
FILER/tmp
\family default
.
 The enviornment variables 
\family typewriter
TMP
\family default
 and 
\family typewriter
TEMP
\family default
 should also be set to 
\family typewriter
~/FILER/tmp
\family default
.

\family typewriter
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection

\bar under
210711B
\bar default
 Installation Homes, 
\family typewriter
~/.local
\family default
, 
\family typewriter
/usr/local
\family default
 and 
\family typewriter
/usr
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Many apps have 
\emph on
Installation Homes
\emph default
 that contain their files and binaries.
 The configuration of these apps is often done through these installation
 homes and many files the app requires are sometimes relative to it.
 Sometimes, and especially in the case of programming langauges, the installatio
n home must be specified in an enviornment variable so apps that have it
 as a dependency can use it properly.
 It can be said that apps are 
\emph on
installed into
\emph default
 their Installation Homes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For NoSeer and MiniSeer, most apps are installed automatically into system
 directories.
 Apps installed via Linux emulation enviornment such as CygWin or Termux
 should follow the same procedures as AllSeer, listed below.
 GSeer is only storage rather than an poerating system and thus apps cannot
 be installed on it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As per the 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "FHS"
target "https://refspecs.linuxfoundation.org/FHS_3.0/fhs/index.html"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, apps on Linux will generally be installed into 
\family typewriter
/usr
\family default
, 
\family typewriter
/usr/local
\family default
 and 
\family typewriter
~/.local
\family default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Apps installed via package managers such as apt or pkg willl be installed
 unto 
\family typewriter
/usr
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Apps installed manually will generally be usually installed into 
\family typewriter
/usr/local
\family default
; 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Apps installed manually that need to be for a specific user will be installed
 into a ~
\family typewriter
/.local/apps 
\family default
directory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Apps created by me will be installed into 
\family typewriter
~/.local/apps
\family default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For Installation Homes that contain the software's binary launchers, often
 the Installation Home's bin directory needs to be added to the 
\family typewriter
PATH
\family default
 environment variable, so its files can be ran by name from terminal.
 An easier alternative is to symbolically link them into 
\family typewriter
/usr/local/bin 
\family default
or 
\family typewriter
~/.local/bin
\family default
, dependant on wether 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
When a software specifically instructs the addition of its Installation
 Home as an enviornment variable, its bin should be added to the path
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
When a software installation contains multiple binaries that are not automatical
ly linked to a normal binary directory, the Installation Home bin should
 be added to 
\family typewriter
PATH
\family default
 via 
\family typewriter
export PATH=$PATH:$INSTALL_HOME/bin
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Otherwise, relevant binary files should be symbolically linked to an identically
 files in 
\family typewriter
/usr/local/bin
\family default
.
 The name of the destination file should be lowercase and with no extension,
 and may be modified in order to be so.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection

\bar under
210711C
\bar default
 XDG Directories, Windows Libraries and Android equivalents
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By default, most operating systems create a few directories upon adding
 a user, for their 
\shape slanted
music
\shape default
, 
\shape slanted
picture
\shape default
s, 
\shape slanted
videos
\shape default
, 
\shape slanted
documents
\shape default
 and 
\shape slanted
downloads
\shape default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For some operating systems, such as Android, these are fully regular files,
 and can be removed in a mostly straightforward manner.
 However, many apps might search for these directories and default to using
 them; worse, these directories may be actively defined and treated in a
 different manner by the operating system.
 For example, Windows defines these as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Libraries
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, that can flatten the file tree to show many relevant files at a glass,
 and inssisently appear at the user's directory; on Linux freedesktop.org
 specifies these directories in 
\family typewriter
~/.config/user-dirs.dirs
\family default
, and certain apps such as Nautilous search for them and use them (e.g as
 permnant bookmarks).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As per 
\shape slanted
System210710A
\shape default
, the 
\emph on
Downloads Directory
\emph default
 should be set as 
\family typewriter
/tmp
\family default
.
 The other media directories though, are unneeded, as content is categorized
 by purpose rather than type, and uncategorized content goes into 
\family typewriter
/tmp
\family default
, again per 
\shape slanted
System210710A
\shape default
.
 Alternatively media directories can all point to 
\family typewriter
/tmp
\family default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\shape slanted
AllSeer
\shape default
 is a Linux OS using freedesktop.org and so sets its media directories in
 
\family typewriter
~/usr-dirs.dirs
\family default
 .
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
In order to delete the Media Directories, set
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
XDG_DOCUMENTS_DIR="$HOME"
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
XDG_MUSIC_DIR="$HOME" 
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
XDG_PICTURES_DIR="$HOME"
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
XDG_VIDEOS_DIR="$HOME"
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In order to point Media Directories to 
\family typewriter
/tmp
\family default
, set
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
XDG_DOCUMENTS_DIR="/tmp"
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
XDG_MUSIC_DIR="/tmp" 
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
XDG_PICTURES_DIR="/tmp"
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
XDG_VIDEOS_DIR="/tmp"
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
At any case, the downloads directory should be set thus:
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
XDG_DOWNLOAD_DIR="/tmp" 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\shape slanted
NoSeer 
\shape default
is a Windows OS and so sets its Media Directories via the Library interface.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
To remove Media Directories, try to delete them like directories via Windows
 Explorer.
 If that does not work properly, additional Registry changes may be required
 (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "here"
target "https://superuser.com/questions/1612043/remove-libraries-from-windows-10-windows-explorer"
literal "false"

\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
To merge the Media Directories into 
\family typewriter
/tmp
\family default
, go into , the properties of each library (right click), click Set Location
 and choose 
\family typewriter
C:
\backslash
Users
\backslash
ataya
\backslash
Home
\backslash
Gray
\backslash
FILER
\backslash
tmp
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Downloads folder should be put as 
\family typewriter
C:
\backslash
Users
\backslash
ataya
\backslash
Home
\backslash
Gray
\backslash
FILER
\backslash
tmp
\family default
 anyway.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\shape slanted
MiniSeer
\shape default
 is an Android OS.
 While Android does create Media directories by default, they have no special
 status and can be removed as any local directory.
 Since they have no special status there is nothing to set to /tmp, and
 so these files indeed should be removed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\shape slanted
GSeer
\shape default
 is not an Operating System and so has no special Media Directories.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection

\bar under
210711D
\bar default
 Desktop Directory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Many operating systems use 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "the desktop metaphor"
target "https://www.wikiwand.com/en/Desktop_metaphor"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 as a basis for their User Interface, in which, there is a consistent screen
 that acts as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

base
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 display, often customizable with a wallpaper, that displays the files found
 in a specified, special, directory.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This paradigm is present on both AllSeer and NoSeer.
 In both, this project should contain a directory 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Desktop
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 which should be set as the Desktop directory, and its content should be
 set by a future gray customization project.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection

\bar under
210712A
\bar default
 Relative Symbolic Links
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to maintain ubiquity among different home directories, 
\series bold
symbolic links should always be relative
\series default
.
 Absolute symbolic links will contain the changin home directory path and
 thus cannot be copied to other file systems in a straightforward manner.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection

\bar under
210728A
\bar default
 Persistent temprary files & the Boidem Directoy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As 
\shape slanted
System210710
\shape default
 states, most files that cannot be categorized either need to have a project
 created for them, or are meant for a concrete action.
 In the latter case, creating them in 
\family typewriter
/tmp
\family default
 is a great way to avoid clutter.
 The same goes for files that are only briefly needed for a particular action
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, 
\family typewriter
/tmp
\family default
 gets cleared on boot, and some uncategorized and temporary files need to
 be kept more persistently.
 Example cases include 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Files whose project was not yet stated
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

dirty
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 backups and tests —mosty disorganized data that cannot be properly organized
 at the moment and yet it is signifcantly prefereble to maintain.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For this porpuse, a directory 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Boidem
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 should be created under this project.
 Apropriate files should be housed, and it should be checked and cleared
 on a weekly basis.
 A file that sits for a month can be deleted, or archived in the closest
 matching class.
\end_layout

